        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/21897",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "This would not work.\n\n*) You can have multiple locales.\nWhen you add new translation files, each one with a locale object, which one should be referenced ? There is no way to select this.\n\n*) What should be done when you change the language of your locale object to a unsupported language ? \nActually a exception is raised, but this could not be done when coupling the locale object. This leads to unexpected behaviour in translation.\n\n*) What if you change the locale object in the middle of a translation ?\nYour translation would change the language which is not wished.\n\nThe decission to NOT HARD-COUPLE locale with translation was made because of this reasons in past and serveral more...",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-05-23T09:54:34.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-05-23T09:54:34.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/21898",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=toxygene",
                        "name": "toxygene",
                        "displayName": "Justin Hendrickson",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Interesting... all good points. My approach of passing a single locale object around my classes is obviously not the correct approach. I obviously need to re-approach the problem from a different angle.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=toxygene",
                        "name": "toxygene",
                        "displayName": "Justin Hendrickson",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-05-23T10:43:24.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-05-23T10:43:24.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/21899",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Let's say, to reference a single locale may fit perfectly in your case.\nBut for the framework we must be more generic.\n\nAnd as you already mentioned it's easy to have only a single locale within your application if you code it right.\n\nWe will close this issue as \"won't fix\"... feel free to add new improvements anytime.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-05-23T10:54:01.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-05-23T10:54:01.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
